body:
@dongjoon-hyun I've found that the CPU cores were the root cause of the problem. As I mentioned above, each Vortex test requests `2 evaluators with 4 CPU cores`. But in my VirtualBox configuration, I found that the number of Processors was only 1(default value). After reducing the number of cores in the test code and increasing the number of Processors to 2 (the maximum allowed to my machine), all tests are passing smoothly.

I agree with your suggestion to cut down resource pressure in integration tests, especially for the virtual environment such as Docker, but this can be tackled in a separate PR. I'll file a JIRA for it.

I'll merge this PR because the problem itself has been resolved.

@anupam128 Overall, only one thing has changed for the user, which is the way they specify the maximum number of submissions. It was erroneously in `DriverConfiguration` when it is really a submission parameter. Furthermore, it is only mainly used in the scenario of Driver Restarts. Provided that it is not really a widely used function of REEF, I propose that we skip the deprecation phase for this, 
I have tested this on a YARN cluster for both submission methods.
Thanks!

@dongjoon-hyun I got one question though. As per the title and description in JIRA, this PR is supposed to update the Mesos version to 0.27.0, but I'm not sure it's done correctly. On the `README.md`, `Mesos-0.27.0` is missing. Only Mesos-0.26.0 is added instead, which is irrelevant to the issue directly.

Could you confirm that the issue is addressed? I might miss something as I'm quite new to Docker, but I'd like to make sure before merging :)

Thanks!
